McCabe-Thiele Analysis Using NRTL Model

This MATLAB code performs distillation analysis for a binary mixture using the NRTL thermodynamic model to calculate equilibrium data. 
It also includes a McCabe-Thiele stepwise calculation and a sensitivity analysis of reflux ratio versus number of stages. 
The code can handle both experimental data and model-based equilibrium curves.

Features
Equilibrium Curve Calculation
  Uses NRTL activity coefficient model to predict vapor-liquid equilibrium (VLE) for a binary mixture.
  Bubble point temperature and equilibrium compositions are calculated using Antoine constants and NRTL parameters.
  Provides a smooth interpolation of the equilibrium curve for plotting and stage calculations.

McCabe-Thiele Method
  Implements the stepwise graphical method to calculate the number of stages required for a given separation.
  Considers both rectifying and stripping sections, as well as a q-line representing feed conditions.
  Can handle fractional stages for improved accuracy.

Operating Lines
  Calculates the rectifying line using the specified reflux ratio R.
  Calculates the stripping line using material balances at the feed intersection.
  Plots the operating lines along with equilibrium and 45° line for visualization.

Sensitivity Analysis
  Computes the effect of varying the reflux ratio (R) on the number of stages required.
  Determines minimum reflux and minimum stripping line slope using NRTL-based equilibrium data.
  Provides insight into optimal column design.

Experimental Data Integration
  Accepts experimental liquid and vapor composition data for comparison with the NRTL model.
  Calculates mean squared error (MSE) to quantify model fit.

Inputs
  P – System pressure (kPa).
  x1_vals – Sweep of liquid mole fractions (0–1) for equilibrium curve calculation.
  ant1, ant2 – Antoine constants for components 1 and 2 [A, B, C].
  b12, b21, alpha – NRTL binary interaction parameters.
  R – Reflux ratio for the rectifying section.
  xd, xb – Distillate and bottom product mole fractions.
  xz – Feed mole fraction.
  q – Feed quality (liquid fraction).
  x, y – Experimental liquid and vapor mole fractions for validation.

Outputs
  Equilibrium Curve – y1star (vapor mole fraction) calculated from NRTL.
  McCabe-Thiele Plot – Operating lines, q-line, and stage stepping.
  Number of Stages – Total stages calculated stepwise with optional fractional stage.
  Sensitivity Analysis Plot – Reflux ratio versus required number of stages.
  MSE – Quantitative error between model prediction and experimental data.

Key Functions
  equilibrium(x1_vals, P, ant1, ant2, parameters)
    Calculates equilibrium vapor mole fraction for each liquid composition using the NRTL model.
  nrtl_bubble(T, x1, x2, P, b12, b21, alpha, ant1, ant2, R)
    Solves bubble point temperature for given composition and NRTL parameters.
  NRTL_minimum_rect(x1_vals, y1star, xd, xz,q)
    Calculates minimum reflux ratio from equilibrium curve and feed conditions.
  NRTL_minimum_strip(x1_vals, y1star, xb, xz,q)
    Calculates slope of minimum stripping line.
  NRTL_minimum_stages(x1_vals, y1star, xd, xb)
    Computes the minimum number of stages required for separation.
  MSE(x, y, P, ant1, ant2, parameters)
    Calculates mean squared error between experimental vapor fractions and model predictions.

How to Use
  Set the system pressure, Antoine constants, and NRTL parameters.
  Define feed, distillate, and bottom mole fractions.
  Run equilibrium to generate NRTL-based VLE curve.
  Use the McCabe-Thiele section to step through stages and plot the column operation.
  Optionally, run sensitivity analysis by varying reflux ratio to study its effect on the number of stages.
  Compare results with experimental data and calculate MSE.

Notes
  The code uses fsolve to solve nonlinear bubble point equations and intersection points.
  NRTL might not be suited for all interactions. I wanted to expand our in class discussion on McCabe Thieve analysis to non ideal systems and NRTL was a property method
  I have noticed in Aspen Plus and was curious on. 
  The stepwise McCabe-Thiele calculation includes a safety break for 50 stages to avoid infinite loops in edge cases. The stepwise McCabe-Thiele analysis can be further
  improved by adding efficiency calculations in future implementations. 
  Sensitivity analysis helps optimize column design and identify practical reflux ratios. Future implementation will be look at with implementing operating costs vs
  capital costs based on this preliminary sensitivity analysis. 

